{"title_page": "Goat tower", "text_new": "\n\n{{good article}}\n{{short description|Farm building}}\n[[File:Johnsons&#039; Goat Tower, brightened.jpg|thumb|Johnsons&#039; Goat Tower, brightened|A goat tower in [[Illinois]], US]]\nA '''goat tower''' is a multi-story decorative goat house, modeled on a European [[folly#Follies in 18th-century French and English gardens|garden folly]], an early example of which was built in [[Portugal]] in the 19th century. The first goat tower was built at {{Interlanguage link|Aveleda (Lousada)|lt=Aveleda|pt||WD=}}, a winery in Portugal's [[Vinho Verde]] region. Since 1981, several other goat towers have been built in South Africa, Norway, the United States, the United Kingdom, and Argentina; these include three at other wineries. The towers typically are multi-story with climbing ramps spiralling the exterior and often become tourist attractions.   \n\n==History==\n[[File:Dwarf goat tower.jpg|left|thumb|226x226px|alt=stone tower with circular stairs|Torre das Cabras at {{Interlanguage link|Aveleda (Lousada)|lt=Aveleda|pt||WD=}}, near [[Penafiel]], Portugal]]\nThe first goat tower was built in [[Portugal]] in the 19th century and modeled on a garden [[folly]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://modernfarmer.com/2014/04/goats-love-playgrounds/|title=Goat Towers: An Idea Whose Time Has Come|last=Brasch|first=Sam|date=16 April 2014|website=[[Modern Farmer (magazine)|Modern Farmer]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171130120439/https://modernfarmer.com/2014/04/goats-love-playgrounds/|archive-date=30 November 2017|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"gardendesign\">American Society of Landscape Architects. [https://books.google.com/books?id=yX1MAAAAYAAJ Garden design] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502032314/http://books.google.com/books?id=yX1MAAAAYAAJ|date=2 May 2014}} \u2013 Volume 18, Issue 5. 1999. \"...Silva da Fonseca, began developing the gardens on a grander scale and building their architectural follies in the 1820s. These are painstakingly maintained today: a stone goat tower three stories high with a spiral ramp of logs...\"</ref><ref>Nic Barlow, Caroline Holmes. [https://books.google.com/books?id=nsRJAQAAIAAJ Follies of Europe: architectural extravaganzas] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502032429/http://books.google.com/books?id=nsRJAQAAIAAJ |date=2 May 2014 }}. 2008 Page 180.</ref> Known as ''Torre das Cabras'' (Tower of the Goats), it was built by Fernando Guedes da Silva da Fonseca (1871\u20131946)<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.drinks-today.com/wine/families-wine-sponsored-reports/aveleda-sa-family-passion-applied-wine|title=Aveleda SA - A family passion applied to wine {{!}} Meiningers Wine Business International|website=www.drinks-today.com|access-date=30 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230194909/https://www.drinks-today.com/wine/families-wine-sponsored-reports/aveleda-sa-family-passion-applied-wine|archive-date=30 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> at Aveleda, near [[Penafiel]], one of the oldest wineries in the [[Vinho Verde]] region of  Portugal.<ref name=\"gardendesign\" /><ref name=\":0\">Aveleda website, http://www.aveleda.pt {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714163304/http://www.aveleda.pt/|date=14 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">[https://visao.sapo.pt/quinta-da-aveleda=f506282 Penafiel: Quinta da Aveleda] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611045135/http://visao.sapo.pt/quinta-da-aveleda=f506282|date=11 June 2015}}. Visao. 27 April 2009.</ref> The tower is three stories with stone walls and a rightward (climbing counter-clockwise) spiral wooden ramp<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308055022/http://www.aveledaportugal.pt/index.php?id=45|title=Aveleda|date=8 March 2018|website=web.archive.org|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gailatlarge.com/blog/2015/03/02/31051|title=Quinta Da Aveleda's Goat Tower|last=Aguiar|first=Gail|date=2 March 2015|website=Gail at large|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910022929/http://gailatlarge.com/blog/2015/03/02/31051|archive-date=10 September 2016|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref> and is one of several follies on the winery's estate for which their Follies label is named.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=http://kronikasvinicolas.blogspot.com/2010/02/no-meu-copo-269-os-follies-da-aveleda.html|title=No meu copo 269 - Os Follies da Aveleda|last=|first=|date=27 February 2010|website=Kr\u00f3nikas Vin\u00edcolas|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230204210/http://kronikasvinicolas.blogspot.com/2010/02/no-meu-copo-269-os-follies-da-aveleda.html|archive-date=30 December 2019|access-date=30 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://europeangardens.eu/inventories/pt/ead.pdf?id=PTIEJP_Norte&c=PTIEJP_Norte_J90|title=Invent\u00e1rio da regi\u00e3o da Norte|publisher=P\u00f4le du document num\u00e9rique, MRSH, Universit\u00e9 de Caen Normandie|year=|isbn=|location=P\u00f4le du document num\u00e9rique|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://revistaadega.uol.com.br/artigo/temos-que-estar-abertos-a-redescobrir-alguns-vinhos_7796.html|title=We have to be open to rediscover some wines: Francisco Guedes Almeida, heir to the Aveleda Group, reveals behind the scenes the succession and challenges of a 1,000-year-old family business|last=|first=|date=|website=Revista ADEGA|language=pt-br|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230210215/https://revistaadega.uol.com.br/artigo/temos-que-estar-abertos-a-redescobrir-alguns-vinhos_7796.html|archive-date=30 December 2019|access-date=30 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Page|first=Karen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5-NHUfFJle8C&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PT143&dq=aveleda+follies&hl=en|title=The Food Lover's Guide to Wine|last2=Dornenburg|first2=Andrew|date=6 December 2011|publisher=Little, Brown|isbn=978-0-316-08406-2|language=en}}</ref> Each of the follies, which in addition to the Torre das Cabras include the [[Manueline|Manuelino-style]] Window, the Tea House, the Four Sisters Fountain, and the Guard House,<ref name=\"gardendesign\" /><ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":16\" /> is represented on one of the winery's labels.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nAccording to Francisco Guedes Almeida, a member of the 13th generation of the Guedes family to own the winery,<ref name=\":1\" /> the goat tower and the estate's other follies are \"artistic daydreams with no functional explanation\" built by various of his ancestors, one of whom \"thought the goats did not belong to the plains&nbsp;... so they built the goat tower, so they could have a mountain.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> The tower symbolizes fertility and abundance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://revistaadega.uol.com.br/artigo/folia-em-terras-lusas_702.html|title=At Quinta da Aveleda, architecture joins nature and becomes much more than just detail. There, architecture is really art|last=|first=|date=15 July 2009|website=Revista ADEGA|language=pt-br|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230213106/https://revistaadega.uol.com.br/artigo/folia-em-terras-lusas_702.html|archive-date=30 December 2019|access-date=30 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/cathyhuyghe/2014/01/27/slideshow-winery-gardens-that-attract-more-attention-than-the-grapes-themselves/|title=Beautiful Winery Gardens That Attract More Attention Than The Grapes Themselves|last=Huyghe|first=Cathy|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=25 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125213538/https://www.forbes.com/sites/cathyhuyghe/2014/01/27/slideshow-winery-gardens-that-attract-more-attention-than-the-grapes-themselves/|archive-date=25 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Almeida, he was travelling in South Africa and stumbled across another goat tower and called an uncle to tell him about it. His uncle told him, \"You're in Fairview,\" and related a story of a 1960s visit from a winemaker from South Africa's [[Fairview Wine and Cheese|Fairview Winery]] who had seen the Aveleda goat tower, was inspired by it, and wrote to the Guedes family to ask permission to build one.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Other goat towers==\n[[File:The goat tower at Henly Hills Farm in Dripping Springs, TX..jpg|thumb|A goat tower in [[Dripping Springs, Texas]]|alt=Round white tower with ledges on the sides|200x200px]]\nFairview built its goat tower in 1981 after the owner's son visited Aveleda and saw their tower.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\">Erica Platter. [https://books.google.com/books?id=8fs5-lBfEIwC A Strange Case of Wine] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102063004/https://books.google.com/books?id=8fs5-lBfEIwC |date=2 November 2017 }}. New Africa Books, 1993 {{ISBN|9780864862600}} p.79  describes the South African Goat Tower as one of a series of 'garden follies' based on European originals.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbn.co.za/news/agriculture/fairview-farm-has-goat-this/|title=Fairview Farm has goat this|last=|first=|date=14 March 2017|website=Cape Business News|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref> The tower is used by the winery's herd of 750 [[Saanen goat|Saanen]], a breed of Swiss mountain goats.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\" />  The tower is two stories and is built of brick and mortar. It has a steeply sloped metal roof and a wooden spiral ramp encircling the tower. It is a tourist attraction in the [[Cape Winelands]] area.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.countrylife.co.za/food-and-wine/fairview-open-skywalk-goats|title=Fairview opens the First Skywalk for Goats|last=Grobler|first=Nicol|date=29 January 2017|website=SA Country Life|language=en-ZA|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe winery uses images of the tower and goats in their branding,<ref name=\":3\" /> producing a wine called Goats do Roam, a pun on [[C\u00f4tes du Rh\u00f4ne AOC|C\u00f4tes du Rh\u00f4ne]], and one called Goat Roti, a pun on [[C\u00f4te-R\u00f4tie AOC|C\u00f4te R\u00f4tie]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/goat-tower-fairview-cheese-wine-farm|title=The Goat Tower of Fairview Cheese & Wine Farm|website=Atlas Obscura|language=en|access-date=18 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930073314/http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/goat-tower-fairview-cheese-wine-farm|archive-date=30 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" /> The names were seen as a derogatory comment on the concept of [[terroir]], which posits that unique environmental factors affect agricultural products such as grapes in ways that preclude calling two wines made from identical grapes grown in different areas by the same name. A 2004 story in ''[[Decanter (magazine)|Decanter]]'' magazine said the name had \"irked France's terroir creator and protector, the INAO ([[Institut national des appellations d'origine|Institut National des Appellations d\u2019Origine]])\", who worry that \"some Americans may not see the difference between the wines\".<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.decanter.com/wine-news/goats-continue-to-roam-despite-rhone-objections-102645/|title=Goats continue to Roam despite Rh\u00f4ne objections|last=Styles|first=Oliver|date=17 February 2004|website=Decanter|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107211936/http://www.decanter.com/wine-news/goats-continue-to-roam-despite-rhone-objections-102645/|archive-date=7 November 2017|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Fairview tower itself inspired others. In 1998, despite not owning any goats,<ref>{{Citation|title=The Great Goat Tower of Shelby County|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NZ3k0wfd488|language=en|access-date=30 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506034343/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NZ3k0wfd488|archive-date=6 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Illinois farmers David and Marcia Johnson built a {{convert|31|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}}, {{convert|8|ft|m|adj=mid|-diameter|abbr=}}<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/travel/a-tower-of-goats-and-other-quirky-illinois-attractions/article_2ce26f83-89e7-552b-b4e4-060e5097b638.html|title=A tower of goats and other quirky Illinois attractions|last=Selbert|first=Pamela|date=15 December 2017|website=stltoday.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707155116/https://www.stltoday.com/travel/a-tower-of-goats-and-other-quirky-illinois-attractions/article_2ce26f83-89e7-552b-b4e4-060e5097b638.html|archive-date=7 July 2018|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref> goat tower in [[Shelby County, Illinois|Shelby County]], near [[Findlay, Illinois|Findlay]], after seeing an article on the Fairview tower in the magazine ''Decanter''.<ref name=\":5\">[http://www.farmshow.com/view_articles.php?a_id=82 31 Ft. Goat Tower Keeps Animals Fit, Happy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919212105/http://www.farmshow.com/view_articles.php?a_id=82 |date=19 September 2013 }} Farm Show Volume 33, Issue 2, 2009.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dalejtravis.com/interest/misc/htm/00492.htm|title=Goat Tower|website=www.dalejtravis.com|accessdate=18 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212513/http://www.dalejtravis.com/interest/misc/htm/00492.htm|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.agriculture.com/livestock/build-it-and-goats-will-climb-it|title=Build It and Goats Will Climb It|last=Huttes|first=Celeste|date=16 September 2019|website=Successful Farming|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918065553/https://www.agriculture.com/livestock/build-it-and-goats-will-climb-it|archive-date=18 September 2019|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref> The tower is constructed of 5000 hand-made bricks and has 276 steps made of concrete slabs reinforced with [[rebar]].<ref name=\":5\" /> It has six stories.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> The Johnsons call their structure \"The Tower of Baaa\".<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> In 2000, the Johnsons purchased 11 Saanen goats,<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2000-10-20-0010210019-story.html|title=Tower in Illinois strictly for the goats|last=Smyser|first=Sue|date=|website=[[chicagotribune.com]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref> and the tower is now used by their herd; Johnson says, \"Goats are the most curious animals in the world so they use the tower a lot. They come and go, passing each other on the ramp.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> The Johnsons' farm, now called Goat Tower Farm, has become a tourist attraction and has had visitors from as far away as Poland and Costa Rica.<ref name=\":6\" />\n[[File:Goat tower at Cholmondeley Castle (geograph 2390773) (cropped).jpg|alt=Brick tower with narrow wooden stair spiraling up the side|left|thumb|200x200px|The goat tower at [[Cholmondeley Castle |Cholmondeley Castle Gardens]] in Cheshire]]\nEkeby, a dairy farm in [[Moss, Norway]], owned by Finn-Erik Blakstad, built a tower based on the Fairview tower and uses images of it in their marketing of the farm's milk and cheese and the on-farm restaurant.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Chef Elizabeth Holm, who runs the restaurant at Ekeby, has a tattoo of the goat tower over most of her back.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 2010, F\u00ednca el Rocio, a goat farm in {{Interlanguage link|Valle de Calamuchita|lt=|es||WD=}} in [[Mendoza, Argentina]], built a goat tower for their herd of [[Anglo-Nubian goat|Anglo-Nubian goats]].<ref name=\"costumbresrurales\" /> The tower, which they call Torre de Cabras, was inspired by the Fairview winery<ref name=\"costumbresrurales\">{{cite news |title=Finca el Rocio Villa Gral Belgrano 3 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YouQnkcUIoM |accessdate=25 January 2020 |publisher=Costumbres Rurales |date=3 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231003056/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YouQnkcUIoM |archive-date=31 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and also built using  the winery's plans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.robinhoodwoods.com/shelbyvillegoattower.htm|title=Shelbyville Goat Tower|website=www.robinhoodwoods.com|access-date=1 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101011304/https://www.robinhoodwoods.com/shelbyvillegoattower.htm|archive-date=1 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It has become a tourist attraction.<ref name=\"costumbresrurales\" />\n\nHampton Roads Winery in [[Surry, Virginia]], claims to have built at {{Convert|34|foot|meter|abbr=}} tall the tallest goat tower in the world to house their herd of [[Nigerian Dwarf goat|Nigerian Dwarf goats]] after reading about the Fairview tower.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypress.com/food-drink/dp-fea-hampton-roads-winery-anniversary-20170513-story.html|title=Hampton Roads Winery: One year in|last=Joseph|first=Natalie|website=dailypress.com|access-date=25 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125211644/https://www.dailypress.com/food-drink/dp-fea-hampton-roads-winery-anniversary-20170513-story.html|archive-date=25 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypress.com/va-vg-wbgmag-hr-winery-0410-story.html|title=Hampton Roads Vineyard & Winery went from a retirement dream to a going concern|last=Centolanza|first=Brandy|website=dailypress.com|access-date=25 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125202903/https://www.dailypress.com/va-vg-wbgmag-hr-winery-0410-story.html|archive-date=25 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The winery has a range of wines named after the tower.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.alignable.com/elberon-va/hampton-roads-winery/goat-tower-wines-jan-2020|title=Goat Tower Wines|website=Alignable|access-date=25 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125202853/https://www.alignable.com/elberon-va/hampton-roads-winery/goat-tower-wines-jan-2020|archive-date=25 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nOther examples include [[Cholmondeley Castle|Cholmondeley Castle Gardens]] in Cheshire, UK, which has a goat tower for their herd of [[pygmy goats]] in the paddocks area<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://livewellservices.cheshireeast.gov.uk/Services/1134|title=Cholmondeley Castle Gardens \u2013 Live Well Cheshire East|website=livewellservices.cheshireeast.gov.uk|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aboutbritain.com/CholmondeleyCastleGardens.htm|title=Cholmondeley Castle Gardens|website=AboutBritain.com|access-date=18 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190221135429/http://www.aboutbritain.com/CholmondeleyCastleGardens.htm|archive-date=21 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and a goat tower built in the outdoor-seating area of Silky O'Sullivan's bar on [[Beale Street]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/silky-osullivans|title=Silky O'Sullivan's|website=Atlas Obscura|accessdate=18 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190518141957/https://www.atlasobscura.com/places/silky-osullivans|archive-date=18 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> where customers sometimes share their beer with the goats.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> In a [[Waunakee]], [[Wisconsin]], goat [[petting zoo]], a steel goat tower built by the Endres Manufacturing Company was designed in a [[Bavaria#Historical buildings|Bavarian]] style to match other buildings in the area.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roadsideamerica.com/tip/25994|title=Waunakee, WI \u2013 Bavarian-Themed Business, Goat Tower|website=RoadsideAmerica.com|accessdate=18 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171025022535/https://www.roadsideamerica.com/tip/25994|archive-date=25 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.endresmfg.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/goat-tower.htm|title=Press Release \u2013 Goat Tower|website=www.endresmfg.com|accessdate=18 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045056/http://www.endresmfg.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/goat-tower.htm|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019 the [[The Maryland Zoo in Baltimore|Maryland Zoo]] built a climbing structure for their herd of goats, calling it a \"goat castle\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Goat Castle|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bTtX0-rKND0|language=en|access-date=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nIn 2014 [[Modern Farmer (magazine)|''Modern Farmer'']] called goat towers \"an idea whose time has come.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> Since at least 2009, the towers have been a [[Internet meme|viral meme]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIt is what it sounds like... a tower for goats.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commonscat-inline|Goat tower}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goat tower}}\n[[Category:Folly buildings in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Goats]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the Western Cape]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the Western Cape]]\n[[Category:Folly buildings in England]]\n[[Category:Folly buildings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Folly buildings in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Folly buildings in Norway]]\n[[Category:Folly towers]]\n[[Category:Agricultural buildings]]\n\n{{Improve categories|date=May 2020}}\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{good article}}\n{{short description|Farm building}}\n[[File:Johnsons&#039; Goat Tower, brightened.jpg|thumb|Johnsons&#039; Goat Tower, brightened|A goat tower in [[Illinois]], US]]\nA '''goat tower''' is a multi-story decorative goat house, modeled on a European [[folly#Follies in 18th-century French and English gardens|garden folly]], an early example of which was built in [[Portugal]] in the 19th century. The first goat tower was built at {{Interlanguage link|Aveleda (Lousada)|lt=Aveleda|pt||WD=}}, a winery in Portugal's [[Vinho Verde]] region. Since 1981, several other goat towers have been built in South Africa, Norway, the United States, the United Kingdom, and Argentina; these include three at other wineries. The towers typically are multi-story with climbing ramps spiralling the exterior and often become tourist attractions.   \n\n==History==\n[[File:Dwarf goat tower.jpg|left|thumb|226x226px|alt=stone tower with circular stairs|Torre das Cabras at {{Interlanguage link|Aveleda (Lousada)|lt=Aveleda|pt||WD=}}, near [[Penafiel]], Portugal]]\nThe first goat tower was built in [[Portugal]] in the 19th century and modeled on a garden [[folly]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://modernfarmer.com/2014/04/goats-love-playgrounds/|title=Goat Towers: An Idea Whose Time Has Come|last=Brasch|first=Sam|date=16 April 2014|website=[[Modern Farmer (magazine)|Modern Farmer]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171130120439/https://modernfarmer.com/2014/04/goats-love-playgrounds/|archive-date=30 November 2017|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"gardendesign\">American Society of Landscape Architects. [https://books.google.com/books?id=yX1MAAAAYAAJ Garden design] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502032314/http://books.google.com/books?id=yX1MAAAAYAAJ|date=2 May 2014}} \u2013 Volume 18, Issue 5. 1999. \"...Silva da Fonseca, began developing the gardens on a grander scale and building their architectural follies in the 1820s. These are painstakingly maintained today: a stone goat tower three stories high with a spiral ramp of logs...\"</ref><ref>Nic Barlow, Caroline Holmes. [https://books.google.com/books?id=nsRJAQAAIAAJ Follies of Europe: architectural extravaganzas] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502032429/http://books.google.com/books?id=nsRJAQAAIAAJ |date=2 May 2014 }}. 2008 Page 180.</ref> Known as ''Torre das Cabras'' (Tower of the Goats), it was built by Fernando Guedes da Silva da Fonseca (1871\u20131946)<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.drinks-today.com/wine/families-wine-sponsored-reports/aveleda-sa-family-passion-applied-wine|title=Aveleda SA - A family passion applied to wine {{!}} Meiningers Wine Business International|website=www.drinks-today.com|access-date=30 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230194909/https://www.drinks-today.com/wine/families-wine-sponsored-reports/aveleda-sa-family-passion-applied-wine|archive-date=30 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> at Aveleda, near [[Penafiel]], one of the oldest wineries in the [[Vinho Verde]] region of  Portugal.<ref name=\"gardendesign\" /><ref name=\":0\">Aveleda website, http://www.aveleda.pt {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714163304/http://www.aveleda.pt/|date=14 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">[https://visao.sapo.pt/quinta-da-aveleda=f506282 Penafiel: Quinta da Aveleda] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611045135/http://visao.sapo.pt/quinta-da-aveleda=f506282|date=11 June 2015}}. Visao. 27 April 2009.</ref> The tower is three stories with stone walls and a rightward (climbing counter-clockwise) spiral wooden ramp<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308055022/http://www.aveledaportugal.pt/index.php?id=45|title=Aveleda|date=8 March 2018|website=web.archive.org|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gailatlarge.com/blog/2015/03/02/31051|title=Quinta Da Aveleda's Goat Tower|last=Aguiar|first=Gail|date=2 March 2015|website=Gail at large|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910022929/http://gailatlarge.com/blog/2015/03/02/31051|archive-date=10 September 2016|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref> and is one of several follies on the winery's estate for which their Follies label is named.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=http://kronikasvinicolas.blogspot.com/2010/02/no-meu-copo-269-os-follies-da-aveleda.html|title=No meu copo 269 - Os Follies da Aveleda|last=|first=|date=27 February 2010|website=Kr\u00f3nikas Vin\u00edcolas|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230204210/http://kronikasvinicolas.blogspot.com/2010/02/no-meu-copo-269-os-follies-da-aveleda.html|archive-date=30 December 2019|access-date=30 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://europeangardens.eu/inventories/pt/ead.pdf?id=PTIEJP_Norte&c=PTIEJP_Norte_J90|title=Invent\u00e1rio da regi\u00e3o da Norte|publisher=P\u00f4le du document num\u00e9rique, MRSH, Universit\u00e9 de Caen Normandie|year=|isbn=|location=P\u00f4le du document num\u00e9rique|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://revistaadega.uol.com.br/artigo/temos-que-estar-abertos-a-redescobrir-alguns-vinhos_7796.html|title=We have to be open to rediscover some wines: Francisco Guedes Almeida, heir to the Aveleda Group, reveals behind the scenes the succession and challenges of a 1,000-year-old family business|last=|first=|date=|website=Revista ADEGA|language=pt-br|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230210215/https://revistaadega.uol.com.br/artigo/temos-que-estar-abertos-a-redescobrir-alguns-vinhos_7796.html|archive-date=30 December 2019|access-date=30 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Page|first=Karen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5-NHUfFJle8C&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&pg=PT143&dq=aveleda+follies&hl=en|title=The Food Lover's Guide to Wine|last2=Dornenburg|first2=Andrew|date=6 December 2011|publisher=Little, Brown|isbn=978-0-316-08406-2|language=en}}</ref> Each of the follies, which in addition to the Torre das Cabras include the [[Manueline|Manuelino-style]] Window, the Tea House, the Four Sisters Fountain, and the Guard House,<ref name=\"gardendesign\" /><ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":16\" /> is represented on one of the winery's labels.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nAccording to Francisco Guedes Almeida, a member of the 13th generation of the Guedes family to own the winery,<ref name=\":1\" /> the goat tower and the estate's other follies are \"artistic daydreams with no functional explanation\" built by various of his ancestors, one of whom \"thought the goats did not belong to the plains&nbsp;... so they built the goat tower, so they could have a mountain.\"<ref name=\":8\" /> The tower symbolizes fertility and abundance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://revistaadega.uol.com.br/artigo/folia-em-terras-lusas_702.html|title=At Quinta da Aveleda, architecture joins nature and becomes much more than just detail. There, architecture is really art|last=|first=|date=15 July 2009|website=Revista ADEGA|language=pt-br|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230213106/https://revistaadega.uol.com.br/artigo/folia-em-terras-lusas_702.html|archive-date=30 December 2019|access-date=30 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/cathyhuyghe/2014/01/27/slideshow-winery-gardens-that-attract-more-attention-than-the-grapes-themselves/|title=Beautiful Winery Gardens That Attract More Attention Than The Grapes Themselves|last=Huyghe|first=Cathy|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=25 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125213538/https://www.forbes.com/sites/cathyhuyghe/2014/01/27/slideshow-winery-gardens-that-attract-more-attention-than-the-grapes-themselves/|archive-date=25 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Almeida, he was travelling in South Africa and stumbled across another goat tower and called an uncle to tell him about it. His uncle told him, \"You're in Fairview,\" and related a story of a 1960s visit from a winemaker from South Africa's [[Fairview Wine and Cheese|Fairview Winery]] who had seen the Aveleda goat tower, was inspired by it, and wrote to the Guedes family to ask permission to build one.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Other goat towers==\n[[File:The goat tower at Henly Hills Farm in Dripping Springs, TX..jpg|thumb|A goat tower in [[Dripping Springs, Texas]]|alt=Round white tower with ledges on the sides|200x200px]]\nFairview built its goat tower in 1981 after the owner's son visited Aveleda and saw their tower.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\">Erica Platter. [https://books.google.com/books?id=8fs5-lBfEIwC A Strange Case of Wine] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102063004/https://books.google.com/books?id=8fs5-lBfEIwC |date=2 November 2017 }}. New Africa Books, 1993 {{ISBN|9780864862600}} p.79  describes the South African Goat Tower as one of a series of 'garden follies' based on European originals.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbn.co.za/news/agriculture/fairview-farm-has-goat-this/|title=Fairview Farm has goat this|last=|first=|date=14 March 2017|website=Cape Business News|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref> The tower is used by the winery's herd of 750 [[Saanen goat|Saanen]], a breed of Swiss mountain goats.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\" />  The tower is two stories and is built of brick and mortar. It has a steeply sloped metal roof and a wooden spiral ramp encircling the tower. It is a tourist attraction in the [[Cape Winelands]] area.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.countrylife.co.za/food-and-wine/fairview-open-skywalk-goats|title=Fairview opens the First Skywalk for Goats|last=Grobler|first=Nicol|date=29 January 2017|website=SA Country Life|language=en-ZA|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe winery uses images of the tower and goats in their branding,<ref name=\":3\" /> producing a wine called Goats do Roam, a pun on [[C\u00f4tes du Rh\u00f4ne AOC|C\u00f4tes du Rh\u00f4ne]], and one called Goat Roti, a pun on [[C\u00f4te-R\u00f4tie AOC|C\u00f4te R\u00f4tie]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/goat-tower-fairview-cheese-wine-farm|title=The Goat Tower of Fairview Cheese & Wine Farm|website=Atlas Obscura|language=en|access-date=18 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930073314/http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/goat-tower-fairview-cheese-wine-farm|archive-date=30 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" /> The names were seen as a derogatory comment on the concept of [[terroir]], which posits that unique environmental factors affect agricultural products such as grapes in ways that preclude calling two wines made from identical grapes grown in different areas by the same name. A 2004 story in ''[[Decanter (magazine)|Decanter]]'' magazine said the name had \"irked France's terroir creator and protector, the INAO ([[Institut national des appellations d'origine|Institut National des Appellations d\u2019Origine]])\", who worry that \"some Americans may not see the difference between the wines\".<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.decanter.com/wine-news/goats-continue-to-roam-despite-rhone-objections-102645/|title=Goats continue to Roam despite Rh\u00f4ne objections|last=Styles|first=Oliver|date=17 February 2004|website=Decanter|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107211936/http://www.decanter.com/wine-news/goats-continue-to-roam-despite-rhone-objections-102645/|archive-date=7 November 2017|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Fairview tower itself inspired others. In 1998, despite not owning any goats,<ref>{{Citation|title=The Great Goat Tower of Shelby County|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NZ3k0wfd488|language=en|access-date=30 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506034343/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NZ3k0wfd488|archive-date=6 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Illinois farmers David and Marcia Johnson built a {{convert|31|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}}, {{convert|8|ft|m|adj=mid|-diameter|abbr=}}<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/travel/a-tower-of-goats-and-other-quirky-illinois-attractions/article_2ce26f83-89e7-552b-b4e4-060e5097b638.html|title=A tower of goats and other quirky Illinois attractions|last=Selbert|first=Pamela|date=15 December 2017|website=stltoday.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707155116/https://www.stltoday.com/travel/a-tower-of-goats-and-other-quirky-illinois-attractions/article_2ce26f83-89e7-552b-b4e4-060e5097b638.html|archive-date=7 July 2018|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref> goat tower in [[Shelby County, Illinois|Shelby County]], near [[Findlay, Illinois|Findlay]], after seeing an article on the Fairview tower in the magazine ''Decanter''.<ref name=\":5\">[http://www.farmshow.com/view_articles.php?a_id=82 31 Ft. Goat Tower Keeps Animals Fit, Happy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919212105/http://www.farmshow.com/view_articles.php?a_id=82 |date=19 September 2013 }} Farm Show Volume 33, Issue 2, 2009.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dalejtravis.com/interest/misc/htm/00492.htm|title=Goat Tower|website=www.dalejtravis.com|accessdate=18 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212513/http://www.dalejtravis.com/interest/misc/htm/00492.htm|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.agriculture.com/livestock/build-it-and-goats-will-climb-it|title=Build It and Goats Will Climb It|last=Huttes|first=Celeste|date=16 September 2019|website=Successful Farming|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918065553/https://www.agriculture.com/livestock/build-it-and-goats-will-climb-it|archive-date=18 September 2019|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref> The tower is constructed of 5000 hand-made bricks and has 276 steps made of concrete slabs reinforced with [[rebar]].<ref name=\":5\" /> It has six stories.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> The Johnsons call their structure \"The Tower of Baaa\".<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> In 2000, the Johnsons purchased 11 Saanen goats,<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2000-10-20-0010210019-story.html|title=Tower in Illinois strictly for the goats|last=Smyser|first=Sue|date=|website=[[chicagotribune.com]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref> and the tower is now used by their herd; Johnson says, \"Goats are the most curious animals in the world so they use the tower a lot. They come and go, passing each other on the ramp.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> The Johnsons' farm, now called Goat Tower Farm, has become a tourist attraction and has had visitors from as far away as Poland and Costa Rica.<ref name=\":6\" />\n[[File:Goat tower at Cholmondeley Castle (geograph 2390773) (cropped).jpg|alt=Brick tower with narrow wooden stair spiraling up the side|left|thumb|200x200px|The goat tower at [[Cholmondeley Castle |Cholmondeley Castle Gardens]] in Cheshire]]\nEkeby, a dairy farm in [[Moss, Norway]], owned by Finn-Erik Blakstad, built a tower based on the Fairview tower and uses images of it in their marketing of the farm's milk and cheese and the on-farm restaurant.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Chef Elizabeth Holm, who runs the restaurant at Ekeby, has a tattoo of the goat tower over most of her back.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 2010, F\u00ednca el Rocio, a goat farm in {{Interlanguage link|Valle de Calamuchita|lt=|es||WD=}} in [[Mendoza, Argentina]], built a goat tower for their herd of [[Anglo-Nubian goat|Anglo-Nubian goats]].<ref name=\"costumbresrurales\" /> The tower, which they call Torre de Cabras, was inspired by the Fairview winery<ref name=\"costumbresrurales\">{{cite news |title=Finca el Rocio Villa Gral Belgrano 3 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YouQnkcUIoM |accessdate=25 January 2020 |publisher=Costumbres Rurales |date=3 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231003056/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YouQnkcUIoM |archive-date=31 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and also built using  the winery's plans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.robinhoodwoods.com/shelbyvillegoattower.htm|title=Shelbyville Goat Tower|website=www.robinhoodwoods.com|access-date=1 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101011304/https://www.robinhoodwoods.com/shelbyvillegoattower.htm|archive-date=1 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It has become a tourist attraction.<ref name=\"costumbresrurales\" />\n\nHampton Roads Winery in [[Surry, Virginia]], claims to have built at {{Convert|34|foot|meter|abbr=}} tall the tallest goat tower in the world to house their herd of [[Nigerian Dwarf goat|Nigerian Dwarf goats]] after reading about the Fairview tower.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypress.com/food-drink/dp-fea-hampton-roads-winery-anniversary-20170513-story.html|title=Hampton Roads Winery: One year in|last=Joseph|first=Natalie|website=dailypress.com|access-date=25 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125211644/https://www.dailypress.com/food-drink/dp-fea-hampton-roads-winery-anniversary-20170513-story.html|archive-date=25 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypress.com/va-vg-wbgmag-hr-winery-0410-story.html|title=Hampton Roads Vineyard & Winery went from a retirement dream to a going concern|last=Centolanza|first=Brandy|website=dailypress.com|access-date=25 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125202903/https://www.dailypress.com/va-vg-wbgmag-hr-winery-0410-story.html|archive-date=25 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The winery has a range of wines named after the tower.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.alignable.com/elberon-va/hampton-roads-winery/goat-tower-wines-jan-2020|title=Goat Tower Wines|website=Alignable|access-date=25 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125202853/https://www.alignable.com/elberon-va/hampton-roads-winery/goat-tower-wines-jan-2020|archive-date=25 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nOther examples include [[Cholmondeley Castle|Cholmondeley Castle Gardens]] in Cheshire, UK, which has a goat tower for their herd of [[pygmy goats]] in the paddocks area<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://livewellservices.cheshireeast.gov.uk/Services/1134|title=Cholmondeley Castle Gardens \u2013 Live Well Cheshire East|website=livewellservices.cheshireeast.gov.uk|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aboutbritain.com/CholmondeleyCastleGardens.htm|title=Cholmondeley Castle Gardens|website=AboutBritain.com|access-date=18 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190221135429/http://www.aboutbritain.com/CholmondeleyCastleGardens.htm|archive-date=21 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and a goat tower built in the outdoor-seating area of Silky O'Sullivan's bar on [[Beale Street]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/silky-osullivans|title=Silky O'Sullivan's|website=Atlas Obscura|accessdate=18 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190518141957/https://www.atlasobscura.com/places/silky-osullivans|archive-date=18 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> where customers sometimes share their beer with the goats.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> In a [[Waunakee]], [[Wisconsin]], goat [[petting zoo]], a steel goat tower built by the Endres Manufacturing Company was designed in a [[Bavaria#Historical buildings|Bavarian]] style to match other buildings in the area.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roadsideamerica.com/tip/25994|title=Waunakee, WI \u2013 Bavarian-Themed Business, Goat Tower|website=RoadsideAmerica.com|accessdate=18 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171025022535/https://www.roadsideamerica.com/tip/25994|archive-date=25 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.endresmfg.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/goat-tower.htm|title=Press Release \u2013 Goat Tower|website=www.endresmfg.com|accessdate=18 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045056/http://www.endresmfg.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/goat-tower.htm|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019 the [[The Maryland Zoo in Baltimore|Maryland Zoo]] built a climbing structure for their herd of goats, calling it a \"goat castle\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Goat Castle|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bTtX0-rKND0|language=en|access-date=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nIn 2014 [[Modern Farmer (magazine)|''Modern Farmer'']] called goat towers \"an idea whose time has come.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> Since at least 2009, the towers have been a [[Internet meme|viral meme]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commonscat-inline|Goat tower}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goat tower}}\n[[Category:Folly buildings in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Goats]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the Western Cape]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the Western Cape]]\n[[Category:Folly buildings in England]]\n[[Category:Folly buildings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Folly buildings in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Folly buildings in Norway]]\n[[Category:Folly towers]]\n[[Category:Agricultural buildings]]\n\n{{Improve categories|date=May 2020}}\n", "name_user": "NoU101", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goat_tower"}
